entum that only a telephone pole or an oversized boulder retards their forward motion absolutely. Sir Isaac Newton called this sudden termination of motion the stooge's surcease. </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br><br>Cartoon Law III <br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    Any body passing through solid matter will leave a perforation conforming to its perimeter.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>   Also called the silhouette of passage, this phenomenon is the speciality of victims of directed-pressure explosions and of reckless cowards who are so eager to escape that they exit directly through the wall of a house, leaving a cookie-cutout-perfect hole. The threat of skunks or matrimony often catalyses this reaction. </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br><br>Cartoon Law IV <br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    The time required for an object to fall twenty stories is greater than or equal to the time it takes for whoever knocked it off the ledge to spiral down twenty flights to attempt to capture it unbroken.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>   Such an object is inevitably priceless, the attempt to capture it inevitably unsuccessful. </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br><br>Cartoon Law V <br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    All principles of gravity are negated by fear. </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>    Psychic forces are sufficient in most bodies for a shock to propel them directly away from the earth's surface. A spooky noise or an adversary's signature sound will induce motion upward, usually to the cradle of a chandelier, a treetop, or the crest of a flagpole. The feet of a character who is running or the wheels of a speeding auto need never touch the ground, especially when in flight. </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br><br>Cartoon Law VI <br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    As speed increases, objects can be in several places at once.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>   This is particularly true of tooth-and-claw fights, in which a character's head may be glimpsed emerging from the cloud of altercation at several places simultaneously. This effect is common as well among bodies that are spinning or being throttled. A `wacky' character has the option of self-replication only at manic high speeds and may ricochet off walls to achieve the velocity required. </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br><br>Cartoon Law VII <br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    Certain bodies can pass through solid walls painted to resemble tunnel entrances; others cannot.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>    This trompe l'oeil inconsistency has baffled generations, but at least it is known that whoever paints an entrance on a wall's surface to trick an opponent will be unable to pursue him into this theoretical space. The painter is flattened against the wall when he attempts to follow into the painting. This is ultimately a problem of art, not of science. </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br><br>Cartoon Law VIII <br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    Any violent rearrangement of feline matter is impermanent.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>    Cartoon cats possess even more deaths than the traditional nine lives might comfortably afford. They can be decimated, spliced, splayed, accordion-pleated, spindled, or disassembled, but they cannot be destroyed. After a few moments of blinking self pity, they reinflate, elongate, snap back, or solidify. </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    Corollary: A cat will assume the shape of its container.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br><br>Cartoon Law IX <br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    Everything falls faster than an anvil.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <p>------<BR>Veeshan hits Warrior for 1000 damage. <BR>Warrior has been slain. <BR>RestOfGroup ponders what to do without a Warrior. <BR>Paladin roars at Veeshan. <BR>Veeshan hits Paladin for 1000 dama